jas elsner art and rhetoric in the arch of titus stanford department of classics skip to navigation department of classics standford university logo header home people programs courses projects news events resources contact jas elsner art and rhetoric in the arch of titus thursday january 12 2012 bldg 110 room 112 5 15pm 7 00pm this talk comes out of a project that looks at the rhetorical functions of roman art and the way roman visual culture constructs itself in relation to discursive patterns theorized extensively by rhetoricians the talk will briefly lay out elsner's position on the issues of rhetoric in roman culture using the arch of titus to explore the visual and material patterns of an artistic rhetorical argument jas elsner is humfry payne senior research fellow at corpus christi college oxford and visiting professor of art history at the university of chicago he was previously a lecturer at the courtauld institute in london and has held various visiting posts in classics or art history departments including ucla michigan princeton and paris currently he is mellon co ordinator for a project on the futures of art history at the institute of fine arts in new york university login to post comments email stanford classics find us on facebook address & phone search recent news faculty grad student group awarded funding for shc research worshop 05 20 2011 stanford classics tops national research council rankings 09 28 2010 scit's production of aristophanes wasps in the spotlight 02 14 2011 see more news site info 2012 stanford university department of classics all rights reserved site design by chapter three login login with sunet speaker request webform for faculty stanford classics wikisite powered by drupal an open source content management system
